[4] USA (Ohio)
Date: Thu 22 May 2014
Source: Coshocton Tribune [edited]
http://www.coshoctontribune.com/article/20140521/NEWS01/305210004/New-measles-cases-confirmed


Coshocton County now has 6 confirmed cases of measles, part of the largest reported outbreak of the disease in Ohio since 1996. Robert Brems Jr,. Coshocton County Health Department health commissioner, said the 2 new cases are Amish men in White Eyes Township. Neither was vaccinated before the outbreak. 4 cases were previously confirmed in Coshocton with 3 in the same family in Crawford Township and another unrelated woman also in Crawford Township. All were Amish and had not been vaccinated. Brems said the men are not directly related to any of the previously confirmed cases, but they did report contact with those patients through work or the community.

The Ohio Department of Health said there are 111 confirmed measles cases in the state; 6 people were hospitalized for it as of [Wed 21 May 2014]. The bulk of the cases, 73, are in Knox County. It's believed the outbreak can be traced back to 4 Amish people in Knox County who had recently returned from a trip to the Philippines. Measles is a highly contagious respiratory disease. The Coshocton County Health Department said 545 people have been vaccinated since the outbreak was announced. Brems said new cases could be reported for a while yet as the disease has a 3-week incubation period before symptoms appear.

As of [Wed 21 May 2014], the state health department reported 366 mumps cases in a separate outbreak. Most were in Central Ohio with none in Coshocton County. Franklin County had the most mumps cases reported with 301.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
