[6] USA (Washington, Montana exposure)
Date: Wed 21 May 2014
Source: KAJ18, Health News [edited]
http://kaj18.com/news/flathead-health-officials-proactive-against-measles-outbreak/


More than 30 people in Washington State have contracted the measles, a virus, that's practically been eliminated from the United States. There haven't been any documented cases of measles in the state of Montana as of yet. But several Montanan's have been exposed to over 30 people in the state of Washington who have contracted the measles virus and that's of concern to the Flathead County Health Department.

At the Flathead County Health Department, Director Joe Russell tells us that despite the fact that Montana appears measles free for right now, which may not last, so they are being proactive, "some of the consequences can be very serious, so we're a little concerned. We've done a really good job at basically eliminating measles. We've had more measles cases over the last year, than we've had over the last 10."

Many of those cases of measles could have been easily prevented by vaccination, something that Joe Russell at the Flathead County Health Department says has kept Measles at bay for many years, "So you start to get a little concerned again, do we have a pool of unvaccinated out there, are they under vaccinated? Those are all things that concern us, so when you start to see cases in Washington, start to see cases in the Midwest, we start to get very concerned."

Russell tells us that even if you are not a fan of vaccination, measles is not something you or your child want to contract. "We travel to Washington, Washingtonians travel here, it's inevitable that we could come in contact with measles, so we have to be concerned, there is no boundary anymore."

[byline: Dax VanFossen]

