[7] USA (Missouri)
Date: Wed 21 May 2014
Source: The Smithville Herald [edited]
http://www.smithvilleherald.com/news/county_and_northland_news/article_e2a02ec5-4cf8-5c6e-a0f3-5ebd3e034fe4.html


The Clay County Public Health Center confirmed 2 new cases of measles within the county Fri 16 May 2014, 3 days after a baby was confirmed to have the illness. All 3 cases are within a single family. The Health Center reported the initial case 13 May 2014. The diagnosed infant had just returned home with its family from an international trip when the symptoms were noticed. The infant received treatment at a local hospital, and household members of the infant's family began to receive appropriate vaccinations to stop the spread of the disease. In a statement, the Health Center confirmed the additional cases involved the mother and sibling of the infected baby.

"This disease can be easily transmitted from person to person in a closed environment. It is not unexpected to see a cluster of measles cases occur within the same household," director of public health Gary Zaborac said in a statement. Staff from the Clay County Public Health Center have continued to monitor members of the family since the initial diagnosis. Darrell Meinke, the health center's division director of administration said members of the health center had conducted visits to the family's home to monitor the current cases and look for signs of additional symptoms. He stated that no member of the family had been previously vaccinated for the disease.

While the Health Center continues to track the situation, it is encouraging residents to check their personal immunization status and that of their family members. 2 doses of the measles, mumps and rubella vaccine are required for an individual to be considered immune. The health center is suggesting those who have not been fully immunized to schedule a vaccination with their health care providers. Missouri's immunization schedule recommends children receive the MMR vaccination for measles, mumps, and rubella when they are between 12 to 15 months old and again between ages 4 and 6 years.

According to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, as of [16 May 2014], a total of 216 cases of measles had been reported in 18 states this year. The mark has already eclipsed the total number of cases that were reported in the United States in 2012 and 2013.

[byline: Ryne Dittmer]

