[9] UK (England)
Date: Fri 23 May 2014
Source: OnMedica [edited]
http://www.onmedica.com/newsarticle.aspx?id=b4b5740c-412e-4153-b4e6-16443bbb4149Onmedica [edited by Mod.CP]


One in 3 cases of measles in England results from overseas travel, show the latest figures on confirmed cases of the infection, published by Public Health England (PHE) today [23 May 2014]. There were 70 measles cases confirmed in England between January and March 2014 -- a significant fall on the figures for the same period in 2013 when 673 cases were confirmed, but an increase on the previous quarter's figures when there were 24 cases. Around 1/3 of all new cases (27) were the result of infection caught while overseas, and 16 were associated with travel to the Philippines where there has been a large outbreak.

During 2013, there were 10 271 cases of measles reported within the European Union [ECDC Surveillance report: Measles and rubella monitoring. February 2014. European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control; http://www.ecdc.europa.eu/en/publications/Publications/measles-rubella-monitoring-february-2014.pdf] Of these, 8 were complicated by acute measles encephalitis and 3 people died. Today's new figures also show there were 847 confirmed cases of mumps in the 1st quarter of 2014, compared to 1036 cases confirmed between January and March 2013, and 520 cases reported in the last quarter of 2013. There were no cases of rubella confirmed between January and March 2014, compared to 3 cases identified in the last quarter of 2013.

"Although the number of cases in England remains low compared to 2012 and early 2013, the 3 deaths recently reported in Europe is a stark reminder of the importance of completing vaccination," commented Dr Mary Ramsay, PHE's head of immunisation. "With measles circulating widely across many parts of the world it is very important that before going overseas on summer holidays people are aware of their own and their family's vaccination status and ensure they have received two doses of the MMR vaccine," she warned. And she added: "Although mumps numbers are high they have decreased when compared to the same quarter of last year [2013] and remain lower than the levels seen in 2004 to 2005, when outbreaks were reported in several universities. This probably reflects the fact that most young people now attending university were eligible for 2 doses of MMR as children."

[byline: Caroline White]

